The Effect of Fans on an NBA Game¶

Introduction¶

The NBA, or the National Basketball Association, was established in 1946. The 2021-2022 season will mark the league's 75th season. In that time, many games have been played at a variety of arenas. Over the years, it has become apparent that home-court advantage is real among many sports, especially basketball. It is possible to believe that home-court advantage can be traced back to the home team's fans that are attending the game.

In 2020, the World was hit by the COVID-19 pandemic causing many sports leagues to shut down for some time, including the NBA. When the NBA came back for the rest of the 2020 season, no fans were present at the games, but teams were playing at a neutral site. However, for the 2020-2021 NBA regular season, teams were back to playing at their home arenas, but with either no fans allowed, or limited fans allowed. So, the question becomes, what role do fans play in an NBA game? How much do they factor into the "home-court advantage" of an NBA team?

In this tutorial, I will go through the data science pipeline to show the effect that fans have on an NBA game. The goal is to collect and tidy some data from the last few NBA seasons, provide some specifics and visualize the home-court advantage with and without fans, and eventually predict the outcome of a home game based on whether fans were present or not.

Parse the Data¶

I am interested in the wins and losses between and home team and away team. Additionally, I want the point differential from games to show what kind of effect fans may have on the competition. Therefore, I will only extract the following columns from the database in the code below. This will help me explore wins depending on home court and attendance.

To explore the data, I am going to want two datasets, one from the season of 2020, and one from a season prior. In [9]:
import seaborn as sns

In order to truly see the effect of point differential on the fans, we will want to manipulate the data a bit. We want to get a measure of point differential across time when it comes to the home team. To do this, we will create a few variables that track the number of games in a day, the total number of home games up to a certain day, and the total home point differential up to a specific game. These variables will help visualize the home court advantage over a season plus the difference fans make in a game.

In [10]:
fans_allowed['NUM_GAMES_DAY'] = fans_allowed.groupby('DAY')['DAY'].transform('count') # Count the number of games per day

# Preventing from the number of games being counted multiple times
fans_allowed['is_dup'] = fans_allowed.duplicated(subset=['DAY']) 

# Copy over the number of games in that day to later be counted
for i, c in fans_allowed.iterrows():
    if (fans_allowed.at[i, 'is_dup'] == False):
        fans_allowed.at[i, 'is_dup'] = c['NUM_GAMES_DAY']
# replace all the dups with 0
fans_allowed = fans_allowed.replace(True, 0)

# Add up all games played up to this day
fans_allowed['TOTAL_HOME_GAMES'] = fans_allowed.is_dup.cumsum()
fans_allowed = fans_allowed.drop(columns = ['is_dup'])
# Add up all pointt dif for all games
fans_allowed['TOTAL_PT_DIF_HOME'] = fans_allowed['HOME_PT_DIF'].cumsum()

fans_allowed

Based on the above linear model, it is clear that there is a relationship between attendance and home point differential as the resulting p value is 0. However, given the scatter plot, it appears that there is more going on than just attendance affecting point differential. Because this is the case, it is important to look at some other factors of the game that could be impacted by the attendance, and ultimately impact the point differential.

Some important factors that can determine the outcome of a basketball game include things like shooting percentage, free throws, turnovers, and rebounds. To get a measure of this, I want to explore the effects that attendance has on the road and home team in these categories by finding the difference in terms of the home team.

The above results show the effects of attendance on various aspects of the game. For one, we can see that field goal percentage, rebounds, and free throws attempted all seem to be related to attendance. Turnovers can be seen to not really be related as the p value for it is large. With this being the case, it will be important to note that we should be considering that attendance can affect some of these factors of the game which also impact the outcome of the game.

# Predict outcome of the game by predicting the point differential based off of attendance
# and other above discussed factors of the game
from sklearn import model_selection
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

testdf = df[['ATTENDANCE', 'HOME_REB_DIF', 'FG_PCT_HOME_DIF', 'FT_HOME_DIF']]

X = testdf
y = df['HOME_PT_DIF']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = model_selection.train_test_split(X, y, test_size = .4)
X_train['HOME_PT_DIF'] = y_train
X_train['ATTENDANCE'] = X_train['ATTENDANCE'].astype(int)
regr = smf.ols(formula = 'HOME_PT_DIF ~ ATTENDANCE + HOME_REB_DIF + FG_PCT_HOME_DIF + FT_HOME_DIF', data = X_train).fit()
preds = regr.predict(X_test)
regr.params
regr.rsquared
